@flexiarg relationship-coherence/rupture-repair
@title Name the Cause, Don't Personalise the Spill
@sigils [🩹/和]
@keywords rupture, repair, self-regulation, de-personalise, reassurance, nervous-system, concord
@audience correspondents weathering emotional over-spills
@references [relationship-coherence/capacity-honoring relationship-coherence/narrative-suspension]
@references-extra ["Instance of origin: 2026-04-02 — Julia, hours after an over-spill on a walk: 'sorry, again, for freaking out a bit! I'll regulate my nervous system and try to figure out what happened... please don't take it personally.' Joe repairs by de-personalising and re-framing as shared journey: 'All part of today's journey, through time and space and a few fairy portals, and a few emotional states. I was pleased to travel with you.' Third-party ratification 2026-05-10 (Chris: 'he's only ever seen you be warm and gentle')."]
@tone practical
@style pattern

! conclusion: When an emotion over-spills, the one who spilled names the cause (and asks the other not to take it personally); the other de-personalises and re-frames the episode as part of a shared journey. Repair, not the absence of rupture, is the coherence signal.

  + context: Intimacy raises the stakes of ordinary dysregulation; over-spills are not failures of the relationship but load tests of its repair machinery. This pair repairs fast and explicitly, which is why the ruptures leave no residue.

  + IF:
    one of you has spilled — snapped, frozen, freaked out, withdrawn — and the moment is still warm enough to be read as being *about* the other.

  + HOWEVER:
    silence lets the other write the worst story (see relationship-coherence/narrative-suspension); but an apology that grovels, or a repair that makes the spiller the problem, deepens the wound instead of closing it.

  + THEN:
    spiller: name the mechanism ('I'll regulate my nervous system', 'please don't take it personally'). Receiver: absorb it without scorekeeping and re-frame as shared ('all part of today's journey'). Close the loop; do not litigate the delivery.

  + BECAUSE:
    a spill de-personalised is a nervous-system event two people move through together; a spill personalised is evidence in a case against the bond. The first keeps concord; the second erodes it. The pattern makes ruptures survivable and even bonding.

  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: ruptures are named, met warmly, and leave no residue in later turns. Failing when: spills go unnamed and unrepaired, or repair curdles into blame-of-the-critic (the deflection is the symptom).
